'''Torvild Aakvaag''' (27 January 1927) was a Norwegian businessperson.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://snl.no/Torvild_Aakvaag |title=Torvild Aakvaag |date=2017-11-03 |website=[[Store norske leksikon]] |language=no |access-date=2018-02-20}}</ref>

He was born in [[Bærum]], and was a [[cand.jur.]] by education. He was employed in the [[Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] from 1951 to 1956, but left for a career in [[Norsk Hydro]]. He was promoted to head of the judicial department in 1967, and head of the petroleum department in 1970. He advanced to become assisting director-general in 1977, and director-general (CEO) in 1984.<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2007|title=Torvild Aakvaag|encyclopedia=Store norske leksikon|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|editor=Henriksen, Petter|url=http://www.snl.no/Torvild_Aakvaag|language=Norwegian|accessdate=22 August 2009}}</ref> He succeeded [[Odd Narud]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://e24.no/kommentar/e24-kommentar/article2861978.ece|title=Kong Reiten ansetter tronfølger|last=Ørjasæter|first=Elin|authorlink=Elin Ørjasæter |date=12 January 2009|work=[[E24 Næringsliv]]|language=Norwegian|accessdate=24 August 2009}}</ref> He stayed in this position until 1991; after this he was chairman of the board from 1992 to 1997.<ref name=snl/> He has also been a board member of [[Orkla Borregaard]], [[Storebrand]] and [[Nobel Industrier]], and chaired [[Hydro Aluminium]] and [[Korn- og Foderstof Kompagniet]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tøffere tider for styrene|last=De Lange|first=Grete|date=30 January 1988|work=Aftenposten|page=5|language=Norwegian|display-authors=etal}}</ref>

He was decorated as a Commander of the [[Royal Norwegian Order of St. Olav]] in 1989.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|year=|title=Torvild Aakvaag|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Gunnar|last=Stavrum|authorlink=Gunnar Stavrum|volume=|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Torvild_Aakvaag/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=22 August 2009}}</ref>

